		<div class="entry-content"><div class="w592"><figure class="media photo promo" itemprop="associatedMedia" itemscope="" itemid="https://static01.nyt.com/images/2014/11/19/opinion/nyto-work/nyto-work-tmagArticle.jpg" itemtype="//schema.org/ImageObject" role="group"><span class="visually-hidden">Photo</span><div class="image"><img itemprop="url" itemid="https://static01.nyt.com/images/2014/11/19/opinion/nyto-work/nyto-work-tmagArticle.jpg" src="https://static01.nyt.com/images/2014/11/19/opinion/nyto-work/nyto-work-tmagArticle.jpg" id="100000003244806" width="592" height="586" alt=""   /><meta itemprop="height" content="586"><meta itemprop="width" content="592"></div><figcaption class="caption" itemprop="description"><span class="caption-text"></span><span class="credit" itemprop="copyrightHolder"><span class="visually-hidden">Credit</span> Barton Silverman/The New York Times</span></figcaption></figure></div>
<div id="sharetools-story" class="sharetools theme-classic sharetools-story" data-shares="email|Email,facebook|Share,twitter|Tweet,save|Save,show-all|More,ad" data-url="//op-talk.blogs.nytimes.com/2014/11/20/when-are-you-not-working/" data-title="When Are You Not Working?" data-description="For some Americans, the answer seems to be ânever.â">
				<div class="ad sharetools-inline-article-ad"></div>
				<div id="MiddleLeft" class="ad middle-left-ad nocontent robots-nocontent"></div>
				</div><p class="p1">âIâm guessing I will do my last work-related task at 12:15 a.m.,â <a href="//thebillfold.com/2014/11/american-workers-want-to-know-when-their-workday-ends/"><span class="s1">writes</span></a> Nicole Dieker at The Billfold. âHow about you?â</p>
<p class="p2"><span class="s2">Sheâs responding to an <a href="//www.theatlantic.com/business/archive/2014/11/the-murky-boundaries-of-the-modern-work-day/382863/"><span class="s1">Atlantic story</span></a> by Gillian B. White, on Americansâ work schedules and how we feel about them. According toÂ a recentÂ </span>Allstate/<span class="s2">National Journal</span>Â Heartland Monitor Poll, Ms. White writes, 28 percent of Americans â and over a third of the full-time employed âÂ would like to work fewer hours. But, she notes: âWhen it came to balancing work and home life, the main complaint seems to be less about overall hours and more about working an unpredictable schedule.â</p>
<p class="p2">âAbout 41 percent of those who are currently employed say that their job frequently requires them to be in contact outside of the office,â she writes. âAnd of those who do check in after working hours, about 56 percent said that they checked in even while on vacation.â River Medina, a transportation manager, tells her,Â âThe only times Iâve taken off were funerals.â</p>
<p class="p3"><span class="s2">Ms. Dieker notes that as a freelancer, she has more control over her time than she did when she worked in an office. âB</span>ut,â she writes, âI also try to keep at least one night a week free for all the overflow work that comes up. And, of course, I answer emailsÂ <i>at all hours</i>.â And, she adds:</p>
<p class="p3">âPeople who work shift jobs have even more unpredictable schedules, and this creates the need for services likeÂ <a href="//thebillfold.com/2014/11/24-hour-daycares-accommodate-the-forever-clock/"><span class="s3">24-hour day cares</span></a>. Knowing when you will work and how long you will be working seems like it would be one of the most basic parts of employment, but it is continuously unclear, often until the moment that it is happening.â</p>
<p class="p4"><span class="s2">For those whose work hours are unpredictable, Jodi Kantor of The Times <a href="//www.nytimes.com/interactive/2014/08/13/us/starbucks-workers-scheduling-hours.html?hp&amp;action=click&amp;pgtype=Homepage&amp;version=HpSumSmallMediaHigh&amp;module=second-column-region&amp;region=top-news&amp;WT.nav=top-news"><span class="s1">reported</span></a>Â in a story focusing on Starbucks, âl</span>egislators and activists are now promoting proposals and laws to mitigate the scheduling problems.â But some, she noted, argue that employers should use their existing scheduling software to generate work schedules that are more humane. She <a href="//www.nytimes.com/2014/08/15/us/starbucks-to-revise-work-scheduling-policies.html"><span class="s1">added</span></a> in a follow-up that Starbucks was indeed changing its scheduling policies in response to her story â the group president in charge of American stores, she wrote, âspecifiedÂ that all work hours must be posted at least one week in advanceâ and âthat scheduling software will be revised to allow more input from managers.â</p>
<p class="p1">But what about that 28 percent who just wish they could spend less time at work? For them, the entrepreneur Nick Hanauer <a href="//www.politico.com/magazine/story/2014/11/overtime-pay-obama-congress-112954.html#.VG0BDFfF8wQ"><span class="s1">suggests</span></a> a fairly simple remedy at Politico Magazine: overtime pay. <span style="color: #3d3c40;">While over 65 percent of salaried Americans qualified for overtime pay in 1975, he writes, only 11 percent did in 2013. Employers arenât required to pay overtime to people in certain roles (like âcomputer professionalâ) as long as they make <a href="//www.dol.gov/whd/overtime/fs17g_salary.htm">$455 or more per week</a> in salary. For someone working a full 52 weeks per year, that works out to $23,660 annually, a figure Mr. Hanauer cites.Â He</span><span class="s4">Â writes:</span></p>
<p class="p2">âWhy, you might ask, are so many workers exempted from overtime? Thatâs a fair question. To be truthful, I have no earthly idea why. What I can tell you is that these exemptions work out very well for your employers.â</p>
<p class="p1">He calls for raising the overtime threshold to $69,000, which would restore overtime to 1975 levels:</p>
<p class="p2">âIn other words, if you earn $69,000 or less, the law would require that you be paid overtime when you worked more than 40 hours a week. Thatâs 10.4 million middle-class Americans with more money in their pockets or more time to spend with friends and family. And if corporate America didnât want to pay you time and a half, it would need to hire hundreds of thousands of additional workers to pick up the slack â slashing the unemployment rate and forcing up wages.â</p>
<p class="p2"><span class="s2">However, heâs not optimistic that this will actually happen: â</span>Officials will very likely raise the overtime threshold just enough to say theyâre doing something, without actually doing much of anything for the middle class or our demand-starved economy at all.â</p>
<p class="p3"><span class="s2">And overtime wouldnât necessarily fix the problem of unpredictable schedules, or work that takes over holidays. Ms. Dieker mentions â</span>the workersÂ asked to skip Thanksgiving so that Black Friday can start a day earlyâ â and Jillian Fisher talkedÂ to some of these workers. According to <a href="//thinkprogress.org/economy/2014/11/19/3594203/kmart-thanksgiving-requests-denied/"><span class="s1">Bryce Covert of ThinkProgress</span></a>, Ms. Fisher started a petition asking Kmart to let employees take Thanksgiving off if they want to.Â One employee told Ms. Fisher,Â <span class="s4">âOur manager stated at a staff meeting: âEveryone must work Thanksgiving and Black Friday. No time off.ââÂ And, Ms. Covert writes:</span></p>
<p class="p2">âMost workers have no idea whether theyâre going to be asked to give up some of their Thanksgiving dinner to come to work, even with the holiday a week away. Forty-three percent of the surveyed employees said they still donât know their schedules for Thanksgiving or Black Friday.â</p>
<p class="p2"><span class="s2">Kmart told ThinkProgress in a statement that âa</span>ssociate schedules are posted, on average, two weeks in advanceâ â and that those who work on Thanksgiving get overtime. Some may prefer the holiday to the extra money, or at least the right to make that choice. ButÂ those dealing with unpredictable schedules may feel that choice is exactly what they lack.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">&nbsp;</p>
<div id="addendums" class="addendums"><div class="story-addendum theme-correction"><strong>Correction: November 21, 2014</strong> <br>An earlier version of this article imprecisely referred to the conditions for exemptions for employersâ paying overtime. Employers are exempt from paying overtime for people who qualify based on their job duties and who are paid on a salary basis at not less than $455 per week. The exemption is not for all those making over $23,660 annually or working in certain jobs.</div></div>	</div>
